ce:caption.ce:simple-para:
The effects of different temperatures (a), pH values (b) and incubation time (c) on the fluorescence quenching of CDs in the presence of 4-NP. (d) PL spectra of CDs response to 4-NP of various concentrations. Inset presents the corresponding photographs under visible light and UV light. (e) The linear response of the quenching efficiency ((F0
                     -F)/F0
                     ) of CDs versus concentrations of 4-NP and its linear fitting (f) within the range from 0.054 to 68 μM. (g) UV–vis absorption spectra of CDs, 4-NP, CDs/4-NP and theoretical curve of CDs + 4-NP. (h) The superposed graphs of 4-NP absorption spectrum and fluorescence spectra of CDs. (i) PL decay lifetime profile of CDs and CDs + 4-NP.

ce:section.ce:para:
Based on the optimum detection parameters, the feasibility of CDs fluorescence sensor for 4-NP determination is further assessed. As recorded in Fig. 2 (d), the blue fluorescence intensity of CDs decreases with the gradual addition of 4-NP. Quantitative data of (F0 -F)/F0 (F0 and F represent the fluorescence intensity of the detection system at 470 nm in the nonexistence and existence of 4-NP, respectively) and concentration of 4-NP is shown in Fig. 2 (e), indicating that the CDs fluorescence can be quenched effectively in the concentration of 4-NP ranging from 0 to 270 μM. Fig. 2 (f) shows the relationship between 4-NP concentration and the fluorescent signal ratio ((F0 -F)/F0 ), which displays a good linear correlation in the range of 0.054–68 μM. Moreover, the LOD and LOQ for 4-NP are as low as 0.054 μM and 0.181 μM (LOD = 3σ/k and LOQ = 10σ/k, where σ denotes the standard deviation of the blank signals, and k is the slope of the linear calibration curve. The relevant parameters for the regression curve are shown in Tables S2-S3), which meets well with the requirement of regulation (the maximum allowable 4-NP content of 0.43 μM) (Wei et al., 2011). Compared with some other reported methods for 4-NP determination (
Table S4
), the method we proposed demonstrates a wide detection linear range and low LOD and LOQ values. Subsequently, the practical application (tap water, wastewater and Yongjiang river water) of CDs for 4-NP residue analysis is performed. Simultaneously, we select the HPLC assay as a reference and calculate the corresponding t-value to evaluate the reliability and accuracy of the proposed method. As shown in Table 1 , the percentage recoveries of 4-NP are in the range of 101.8–107.5% with the relative standard deviation in percentage (%RSD) less than 1.66%, indicating the reliability of the sensor. Furthermore, the reasonable t-values at a confidence level verify that there are no obvious differences in sensing performance of two methods (Li & Guo, 2023). Therefore, our sensing strategy is quite pragmatic and suitable for the requirement of 4-NP monitoring.
